          <div class="small-8 large-centered columns">
            <p>A corpus of the epigraphic evidence</p>
          <p>Charlotte Roueché</p>

              <p>The aim of this publication is to present all currently known inscribed references to the Circus Factions in the eastern empire, beyond Constantinople, in the fullest possible form. 
              A collection of this kind was first made in 1966 by Α. Christophilopoulou, in  'οἱ ἐκτὸς τῆς Κωνσταντινοπόλεως Βυζαντινοὶ Δῆμοι', in 
              <hi rend="italic"> Charisterion Orlandou</hi>; Alan Cameron then developed this in an Appendix to his 1976 study, 
              <hi rend="italic">Circus Factions</hi> (see further Bibliography/Concordance). An expanded list was collected for a publication in 2020, C. Roueché, 
              'Celebrity and Power: Circus Factions forty years on', in <hi rend="italic">Late Antique Studies in Memory of Alan Cameron</hi>, 
                edited by W. Harris, and A. Hunnel Chen.
            </p>
            <p>The collections named above were simple assemblies of texts, without the opportunity to present them in context. Cameron presented the items 
              by geographical area: for the geographic distribution see Index of Findspots, indices/epidoc/findspot.html. This perhaps obscures other differentiating features. 
              Some of the locations are in auditoria, as might be expected, or in streets, where they reflect the involvement of the Factions in Public ceremonail activities. 
              But some are found in a domestic context - and two are associated wi      th churches.<!-- refer to monument type --></p>
            
            
